 Harris campaign. We also saw the House Democrats most likely gain a seat. =
By no means am I trying to say that there=E2=80=99s no issue and that every=
thing=E2=80=99s good. But let=E2=80=99s actually diagnose what the Harris c=
ampaign did wrong, what they did right, and how we can learn from that. Wha=
t it all comes down to is that we need a really significant change in cultu=
re among leadership in the Democratic
Party=E2=80=94how we=E2=80=99re staffing our teams, how we=E2=80=99re givin=
g directives to our teams, and making sure that the thing we=E2=80=99re mos=
t fearful of is losing, not meeting some level of righteousness that will g=
ive us a good feeling for the rest of our lives.

I don=E2=80=99t know whether we can blame it entirely on Harris.

I=E2=80=99ve lost more elections than I=E2=80=99ve won, and I can tell you =
that when you win, you look like a genius, and when you lose, you look like=
 an idiot, and neither is true. So I=E2=80=99m not blaming Harris=E2=80=99s=
 team or even the vice president, herself. I think they tried their hardest=
=2E What we saw was a failure to commun=
icate. It felt like her campaign was c=
onsistently operating from a place of fear, and I=E2=80=99m trying to diagn=
ose where that fear emanates from. When Democrats are fearful, you start to=
 see that absence of coherence in proposals and ideas, and they can=E2=80=
=99t communicate in simple, clear ways that break through.

We need to change the
culture of the Democratic Party to be aligned with winning and simplicity. =
Screw the nuance, because if you can=E2=80=99t win, you can=E2=80=99t help =
people. We don=E2=80=99t have to sacrifice our values and who we are to be =
winners. But as a party, we know that we answer to the electorate and not t=
o interest groups that are purely there to focus on their singular issue an=
d are not often thinking about mass electoral politics.

Is there anything in Trump=E2=80=99s messaging or campaign that you think w=
