          <td style=3D"padding-bottom: 36px; color: #000000; font-size: 16p=
x; line-height: 30px; margin-top: 0; margin-bottom: 0;"><b><i>Tara Palmeri<=
/i>: How do you see the future of your party?</b><br/><br/><i>Max Rose</i>:=
 I think we have to diagnose what actually happened here; it=E2=80=99s not =
some abject denunciation of the Democratic Party. In fact, 2016 and 2020 we=
re more like that. In =E2=80=9916 and =E2=80=9920, the Democrats did not wi=
n a single statewide race in a state that Trump won; this year, we won four=
=2E <br/><br/>So what you=E2=80=99re seein=
g here is, first and foremost, a fa=
ilure of the <b>Harris </b>campaign. We also saw the House Democrats most l=
ikely gain a seat. By no means am I trying to say that there=E2=80=99s no i=
ssue and that everything=E2=80=99s good. But let=E2=80=99s actually diagnos=
e what the Harris campaign did wrong, what they did right, and how we can l=
earn from that. What it all comes down to is that we need a really signific=
ant change in culture among leadership in the Democratic
Party=E2=80=94how we=E2=80=99re staffing our teams, how we=E2=80=99re givin=
g directives to our teams, and making sure that the thing we=E2=80=99re mos=
t fearful of is losing, not meeting some level of righteousness that will g=
ive us a good feeling for the rest of our lives.<br/><br/><b>I don=E2=80=99=
t know whether we can blame it entirely on Harris.</b><br/><br/>I=E2=80=99v=
e lost more elections than I=E2=80=99ve won, and I can tell you that when y=
ou win, you look like a genius, and when you lose, you look like an idiot, =
and neither is true. So I=E2=80=99m not blaming Harris=E2=80=99s team or ev=
en the vice president, herself. I think they tried their hardest. What we s=
aw was a failure to communicate. It felt like her campaign was consistently=
 operating from a place of fear, and I=E2=80=99m trying to diagnose where t=
hat fear emanates from. When Democrats are fearful, you start to see that a=
bsence of coherence in proposals and ideas, and they can=E2=80=99t communic=
ate in simple, clear ways that break through. <br/><br/>We need to change t=
he
culture of the Democratic Party to be aligned with winning and simplicity. =
Screw the nuance, because if you can=E2=80=99t win, you can=E2=80=99t help =
people. We don=E2=80=99t have to sacrifice our values and who we are to be =
winners. But as a party, we know that we answer to the electorate and not t=
o interest groups that are purely there to focus on their singular issue an=
d are not often thinking about mass electoral politics.<br/><br/><b>Is ther=
e anything in Trump=E2=80=99s messaging or campaign that you think worked a=
nd the Democrats should borrow?</b><br/><br/>With the obvious precursor tha=
t I find Trump to be an abhorrent human being, the simplicity of his messag=
ing is critical. There=E2=80=99s no doubt he=E2=80=99s good at branding. Th=
e other thing that is not as often acknowledged about the Trump campaign is=
 it very clearly sought to engage in cultural communication and cultural tr=
ust-building, whether he=E2=80=99s walking out at a UFC fight or going to t=
he varied podcasts.<br/><br/>One of the hopes is that
the Democratic Party will begin to understand that voting is not always an =
act of self-interest, but also an act of self-expression. And if we complet=
ely ignore that element of decision-making, we=E2=80=99ll continue to fall =
short. We have the country largely unified around what we=E2=80=99re doing,=
 but not feeling like they=E2=80=99re emotionally, culturally, and psycholo=
gically aligned with where we are as people. And that=E2=80=99s something w=
e can fix.<br/></td>
         </tr>
